In article <CwrrEL.1oL@apollo.hp.com>,
Bill Sommerfeld <sommerfeld@apollo.hp.com> wrote:
>His description to me was that in order to make any sense of the
>results when attempting to factor a number <n>, one had to be able to
>distinguish between <n> different angular positions.  When <n> is near
>2**1024, this is very difficult.

This description is wrong.  You only have to distinguish between
about 1000 different angles.  See Coppersmith's paper that Shor's
refers to.  With Shor's original method it is slightly worse, but
still nothing like 2**1024.
